::It doesn't take a keen eye to notice that this emergency phone seems to be quite old, considering its technological composition as well as its current condition.::

::The relative proximity of the railroads, and the phone station's overall design, undoubtedly point to its purpose; they are to be used in situations which involve undesired circumstances when it comes to the functionality of railroad traffic.::

::Typically, these phones feature an interface which has six distinct buttons, each with a unique icon on them. The phone uses a coil cord, and the headphone itself has no additional features other than a speaker and a receiver. Lastly, an exposed digital display port lies right beneath a small metal door, both located under said buttons. The connector's pins are bulky but few in number. ::

::[Hacking or Electronics] Attempt to fix the phone.::

::At first, it's quite obvious that someone has deliberately made changes to the way the this phone operates. Some curious yet strange upgrades have been made to a portion of the transistors used to handle transmission. However none of these additions seem to function as the wiring inside is in total ruin.

Utilizing relatively basic knowledge of electronics, you manage to reconnect all severed wires back to normal. After that, you locate the power switch inside and, for a good measures sake, decide to restart the entire device. A few seconds go by, and now, the phone is active once more.::

::The wires inside are severed in various ways. It's crystal clear to you where the wires used to begin, but, you cannot make out where they would've ended. For now you decide to leave the phone as it is.::
::The call lingers for a moment before it cancels on its own.::

::A robotic voice speaks up:

"Support is on the way. Please stand by."::

:: The first sound you hear is one that would leave your ears bleeding had it lasted longer than a few seconds. The noise clanks mercilessly, producing piercing sounds, some robotic and the others of raw metal, making it seem as if the headphone is being dragged along a rough surface. Suddenly a sharp - *thunk* sound, stops this madness. An old voice shouts:

"There's no crunching happening, stop buzzing me!" 

The call has ended.::

::The problem at hand is a difficult one. Raw force has obliterated most of the components essential for all of the calls to work. There is however, a relatively intact section of the phone linked to one of the buttons. It is there where you find room for modifications and after some tinkering, you manage to make it work. The button itself is missing but a call can be made by stimulating the right electrical signal.::
::The inside of the box resemble a crime scene. Furious pummeling has left little to work with; it was shown no mercy. The knowledge and skill required to fix this device exceed your own.::
::The metal doors behind you click. For a little while, the call hangs open before it gets canceled.::
::The buttons glow in red color. This is the initial sequence to solve.::
::The buttons now glow in green color. Previously inserted sequence was successful.::
::The buttons now glow in blue color. This must be the final sequence to solve.::
::The lights on the orange box starts to flicker, its colors begin to rapidly shift from one to another before eventually turning off. After that, the phone begins to ring; someone's calling.::

::The buttons on the orange box glow in dim white color. This color slowly fades out, before the device turns off.

In the same time, on your right, in the nearby store, you can hear some noise coming out of the shelves; they're moving around.::
::The buttons on the orange box glow in dim white color. This color slowly fades out, before the device turns off.::
::The buttons on the orange box glow in dim white color. This color slowly fades out, before the device turns off. As soon as it does, the nearby metal doors unlock.::
::The buttons on the orange box glow in dim white color. This color slowly fades out, before the device turns off. A moment later, the nearby metal doors unlock.::
::The buttons on the orange box glow in dim white color. This lasts for a few seconds before the the device turns off.::

::This time the silence lasts considerably longer. Suddenly, two distinct yet heavily muffled male voices start talking one to another, but it's impossible to discern much from their conversation. Your attempts to talk to them are futile as it seems you can only listen in on their conversation. By the tone of their voice, it's clear that one party is dissatisfied with the other. Yelling ensues and you can hear the last sentence which sounded like: "I'm done crunching for you, derailed maggots!". The other guy tries to respond: "Aww, Ph-reakyyy, don't leave us hanging. It'll just take--" the call suddenly ends.::
